sec.p:
Prokaryotic and eukaryotic microorganisms establish an intestinal microbiome in mammals (

; 

). Metabolites and metabolic signals of intestinal microorganisms are beneficial for defining the trajectory toward host health or disease, especially early in life (

; 

; 

). Some studies have demonstrated that changes in the microbiome are associated with host physiological disorders and increased susceptibility to inflammation and metabolic and neurogenic diseases (

; 

). For example, 

Saccharomyces boulardii

is a yeast probiotic that is able to prevent and treat pathogenic bacterial infections and intestinal complications (

). To date, studies on gut microbiota have mainly focused on bacteria; however, intestinal fungi are an integral part of a wide variety of human gut microbial environments, and their functional ecological role in human gut microbiomes is still unclear (

). Therefore, enhancing the study of metabolites of intestinal fungi is very important to elucidate the underlying relationship between gut fungi and the host (

; 

).

The genus 

Penicillium

is a cosmopolite ascomycetous fungus widely distributed in marine and terrestrial environments, as well as in the human gut. This genus comprises more than 300 species, and some species are capable of elaborating metabolites with peculiar structural features and significant biological activities, including alkaloids (e.g., penazaphilones A–I) (

), sesquiterpene coumarins (e.g., penisarins A and B) (

), cyclic peptides (psychrophilins B and C) (

), and polyketides (e.g., minolutelides A and B, sclerotiorin, and citrofulvicin) (

; 

). Some metabolites display anti-inflammatory, antiproliferative, and anti-osteoporotic activities, as well as the inhibition of lipoxygenase-1 (

; 

; 

), which has attracted attention from pharmacists and chemists.

Penicilloxaline A ( 1 ) was isolated as an amorphous powder, and its molecular formula was determined to be C 27 H 39 N 3 O 3 based on its HRESIMS ion at m/z 452.2926 [M H] (calcd. for C 27 H 38 N 3 O 3 , 452.2919) and 13 C NMR data. The 1 H NMR data of 1 ( Table 1 ) revealed the presence of a tri-substituted benzene ring at δ H values of 7.34 (1H, d, J = 7.6 Hz, H-4), 6.98 (1H, d, J = 7.6 Hz, H-6), and 6.91 (1H, t, J = 7.6 Hz, H-5), one N -methyl group at δ H 2.46 (1H, s, CH 3 -18), and three methyl groups at δ H 1.15 (1H, s, CH 3 -28), 0.90 (1H, s, CH 3 -23), and 0.77 (1H, s, CH 3 -22). The 13 C NMR data ( Table 1 ) showed 27 carbon signals, including one amide carbonyl carbon at a δ C 181.0, six aromatic carbons at δ C 142.5, 130.2, 129.7, 123.8, 121.3, and 120.7, two oxygenated carbons at δ C 75.7 and 73.2, three nitrogenated carbons at δ C 63.3, 54.8, and 49.7, one N -methyl caron at δ C 28.7, and three methyl carbons at δ C 24.5, 23.2, and 22.8. Comparison of the 1 H and 13 C NMR data from 1 with penioxalamine A isolated from
P. oxalicum TW
01-1 (
) indicated differences at C-18, C-25, and C-26. The chemical shift values of C-25 and C-26 were deshielded from δ C values of 60.1 and 55.6 in penioxalamine A to δ C 75.7 and 73.2 in 1 (
), and the C-18 chemical shift value was shielded from δ C 174.7 in penioxalamine A to δ C 28.7 in 1 (
). The HMBC correlations of CH 3 -28 with C-25/C-26 and the shift values of C-25 ( δ C 75.7) and C-26 ( δ C 73.2) suggested the locations of two hydroxyl groups at C-25 and C-26 ( Fig. 2 ). The HMBC correlation of CH 3 -18 with C-11 revealed that the N -methyl group was linked at C- 11 in a combination of the proton signal of the N -methyl group ( δ H 2.46, s). In the NOESY spectrum of 1 , cross-peaks of CH 3 -28 with CH 3 -22/H-25, H-20 with CH 3 -22/H-13, and CH 3 -23 with H-4/ CH 3 -18 suggested α -orientations of CH 3 -18, OH-25, and OH-26, β -orientations of H-13, H-20, and CH 3 -28 ( Fig. 3 ), and a ( R *)-configuration of C-3. To determine the absolute configuration of 1 , quantum chemical calculations were applied based on DFT. The calculated ECD spectrum of (3 R ,11 R ,13 S ,20 S ,25 S ,26 S )- 1 at the CAM-B3LYP/def-tzvp level agreed with its experimental ECD spectrum ( Fig. 4A ), demonstrating the (3 R ,11 R ,13 S ,20 S ,25 S ,26 S )-configuration of 1 . Accordingly, the structure of 1 is shown in Fig. 1 and is referred to as penicilloxaline A.

The molecular formula of penicilloxaline B ( 2 ) was determined to be C 13 H 14 N 2 O 6 according to its HRESIMS data at m/z 293.0779 [M H] (calcd. for C 13 H 13 N 2 O 6 , 293.0779) and 13 C NMR data. The 1 H NMR data ( Table 2 ) for 2 displayed the presence of two substituted benzene rings at δ H 7.86 (1H, dd, J = 7.9, 1.5 Hz), 7.68 (1H, dd, J = 8.5, 1.5 Hz), 7.53 (1H, td, J = 8.5, 1.5 Hz), and 6.92 (1H, dd, J = 7.9, 1.5 Hz), and a methoxy group at δ H 3.60 (1H, s). The 13 C NMR data ( Table 2 ) for 2 showed 13 carbon resonances, including three carbonyl carbons at δ C 173.0, 168.4, and 163.4, six aromatic carbons at δ C 145.9, 134.2, 131.2, 119.6, 113.2, and 112.2, an olefinic carbon at δ C 131.4, and a methoxy group at δ C 51.2. The 1 H and 13 C NMR data of 2 were similar to those of penipacid C ( 19 ) isolated from
P. paneum
SD-44 (
), with the exception that 2 had three carbons ( δ C 173.0, 51.2, and 30.3) more than 19 and the chemical shift value of C-12 was deshielded from δ C 11.4 in 19 to δ C 29.1 in 2 (
), indicating their differences mainly at the side chain of C-12. This deduction was further confirmed through an HMBC experiment showing correlations of H 2 -12 with C-11/C-14, H-13 with C-9, and OCH 3 -14 with C-14 ( Fig. 2 ). Therefore, the structure of 2 was defined as shown in Fig. 1 and is referred to as penicilloxaline B.

HRESIMS and 13 C NMR data analysis of penicilloxaline H ( 8 ) indicated that its molecular formula was C 14 H 24 O 6 . Comparison of the 1 H and 13 C NMR data of 8 and ( Z , R )-3,7-dimethyl-oct-2- ene-1,6,7-triol revealed the presence of a succinic acid moiety [ δ C 173.7, 172.1, 28.9, and 28.8] and the downfield shift of C-1 from δ C 57.5 in ( Z , R )-3,7- dimethyl-oct-2-ene-1,6,7-triol to δ C 60.6 in 8 (
), which suggests that 8 was a succinylation derivative of the known compound. This deduction was confirmed by the HMBC experiment ( Fig. 2 ). The configuration of the Δ 2(3) olefinic moiety was determined as the ( Z )-configuration based on NOESY cross-peaks of H-2 with CH 3 -9 and H 2 -1 with H-4a ( Fig. 3 ). The optical rotation of 8 was similar to that of ( Z , R )-3,7-dimethyl-oct-2-ene-1,6,7-triol (
), requiring a (6 R )-configuration.

Penicilloxaline I ( 9 ) was assigned a molecular formula of C 10 H 18 O 5 based on its HRESIMS ion at m/z 217.1074 ([M H] calcd. for C 10 H 17 O 5 , 217.1076) and 13 C NMR data ( Table 4 ). The 1 H and 13 C NMR data of 9 closely resembled those of (6 S )-3,7-dimethyl-6,7-dihydroxy-2 ( Z )-octenoic acid ( 15 ) (
). The downfield shift of C-8 from δ C 24.7 in (6 S )-3,7-dimethyl-6,7-dihydroxy-2( Z )-octenoic acid ( 15 ) to δ C 66.2 ( 9 ) suggested the location of a hydroxy group at C-8 (
), which was further confirmed through an HMBC experiment showing correlations of CH 3 -10 with C-8. The configuration of the Δ 2(3) olefinic moiety in 9 was the same as that of 8 described by the NOESY correlations of CH 3 -9 with H-2. Thus, the structure of penicilloxaline I ( 9 ) was identified as shown in Fig. 1 .

