Analysis of the 3D crystal structure of FXR (PDB code: 3BEJ) revealed that this protein (Q96RI1-2, NM_005123) is one of five FXR isoforms (Q96RI1-1, Q96RI1-2, Q96RI1-3, Q96RI1-4, and Q96RI1-5) based on the UniProt database (https://www.uniprot.org/uniprot/Q96RI1), while the FXR plasmid used in this study was cloned from Q96RI1-4 (NM_001206992). A comparison of the amino acid sequences of Q96RI1-2 and Q96RI1-4 suggests that the former possesses ten fewer amino acids than the latter, as previously described (
,
). On the basis of this analysis, a site-directed amino acid mutation was carried out. The S342V mutation abolished the agonistic effect of compound 18 toward FXR ( Fig. 8B ), which further reveals the agonistic effect of compound 18 toward FXR through the hydrogen bond interaction with amino acid residue Ser332.

Conformational searches were conducted with Spartan using the Merck molecular force field (MMFF) with standard parameters (

), and the conformers were subjected to geometry optimization at the B3LYP-D3(BJ)/def2-svp level by DFT calculations with the IEFPCM model in a methanol solution using the Gaussian 16 package (

). Based on the DFT energies, conformers with a Boltzmann distribution ≥1% were chosen. The ECD calculations were performed with the CAM-B3LYP functional and the def-tzvp basis set with the same solvent as in the preceding DFT optimization step.

The agonistic effects of compounds against FXR were measured as previously described, using chenodeoxycholic acid (CDCA, 80 μM) as the positive control (
,
). Human hepatoma HepG2 cells were transiently transfected with human FXR cDNA (Q96RI1–2, NM_005123) and luciferase pGL3.0 vector with the FXRE reporter (basic bile salt export pump BSEP) with the pcDNA3.1 vector expression plasmid, and the null-Renilla luciferase plasmid was used as an internal control. HepG2 cells were treated with vehicle DMSO (0.1%) or compounds after 24 h of transfection. HepG2 cells were harvested after 24 h incubation, and luciferase activity was measured using the Dual-- Luciferase® Reporter Assay System (Promega, USA ). All experiments were repeated three times, and the EC 50 value was analyzed by GraphPad Prism software.

The agonistic effects of compounds against PXR were determined as previously described, using chenodeoxycholic acid (CDCA, 80 μM) as the positive control (

). HepG2 cells were transiently transfected with the expression plasmid of hPXR cDNA and hPXR XREM-driven luciferase reporter plasmid (CYP3A4XREM-luciferase), and pGL4.74 (Promega, 
China
) was used as an internal standard. HepG2 cells were treated with vehicle DMSO (0.1%) or compounds after 24 h of transfection. HepG2 cells were harvested after 24 h incubation, and luciferase activity was measured using the Dual-Luciferase® Reporter Assay System (Promega, 
USA
). All experiments were repeated three times, and the EC 
50
value was analyzed by GraphPad Prism software.

The crystal structure of protein FXR (PDB ID 3BEJ) was downloaded from the Protein Data Bank, and the active pocket of FXR was defined according to its ligand. The 3D structure of compound 
18
was optimized at the CHARMm force field, and then the potential interaction of compound 
18
with FXR was analyzed by the CDOCKER tool in Discovery Studio 2016 (

, 

). The GROMACS package was used to investigate the MD simulation using the AMBER99SB force field (

; 

, 

; 

; 

). The best pose of compound 
18
with FXR was subjected to the steepest descent energy minimization to relax the system. All the parameters were set as default in this calculation. The GROMACS package was used to analyze the root mean square deviation (RSMD), root mean square fluctuations (RMSF), and other parameters, and the results were plotted by GraphPad Prism and PyMOL software.
